04383nam a22006255i 9780226591315DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265913157 a10.7208/97802265913152doi  a(DE-B1597)524437  a(OCoLC)1062360530  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aDG812.4b.L59 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a307.34160945632090312231 aLong, Pamela O., eauthor.10aEngineering the Eternal City :bInfrastructure, Topography, and the Culture of Knowledge in Late Sixteenth-Century Rome /cPamela O. Long. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b73 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMoney, Weights, and Measures -- tAuthor's Note -- tIntroduction -- t1. Troubled Waters: The Tiber River -- t2. The Streets and Sewers of Rome -- t3. Repairing the Acqua Vergine: Conflict and Process -- t4. Contested Infrastructure -- t5. Roman Topography and Images of the City -- t6. Maps, Guidebooks, and the World of Print -- t7. Reforming the Streets -- t8. Engineering Spectacle and Urban Reality -- tConclusion: A City in Transition -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween the catastrophic flood of the Tiber River in 1557 and the death of the "engineering pope" Sixtus V in 1590, the city of Rome was transformed by intense activity involving building construction and engineering projects of all kinds. Using hundreds of archival documents and primary sources, Engineering the Eternal City explores the processes and people involved in these infrastructure projects-sewers, bridge repair, flood prevention, aqueduct construction, the building of new, straight streets, and even the relocation of immensely heavy ancient Egyptian obelisks that Roman emperors had carried to the city centuries before.   This portrait of an early modern Rome examines the many conflicts, failures, and successes that shaped the city, as decision-makers tried to control not only Rome's structures and infrastructures but also the people who lived there. Taking up visual images of the city created during the same period-most importantly in maps and urban representations, this book shows how in a time before the development of modern professionalism and modern bureaucracies, there was far more wide-ranging conversation among people of various backgrounds on issues of engineering and infrastructure than there is in our own times. Physicians, civic leaders, jurists, cardinals, popes, and clerics engaged with painters, sculptors, architects, printers, and other practitioners as they discussed, argued, and completed the projects that remade Rome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCivic improvementzItalyzRomexHistoryy16th century. 0aMunicipal engineeringzItalyzRomexHistoryy16th century. 0aUrban renewalzItalyzRomexHistoryy16th century. 4aRome. 4aTiber River. 4aaqueducts. 4aengineering. 4aflood control. 4ainfrastructure. 4amaps. 4aobelisks. 4asewers. 4astreets. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226591315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226591315.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles